1. Introduction¶

In recent years there has been an increasing interest in the Cost of living around the world. Some are claiming that we are in, as the World Economic Forum puts it, a cost of living crisis. With the increasing uncertainty of the state of the world, many have become uneasy about how their stability of life will be maintained. Mainly how the relationship between what they have to spend and how much money they are making.

In this tutorial, we will analyze and attempt to understand the relationship between cost of living and salary along with other metrics.

Our goal is to determine if around the world people are being given a fair salary that is proportionate to the cost of living.

We want to know if payemnt meets the price required of living. Are people being fairly given a living wage, what places have the most cost and least salary, what places have the least cost and most salary?

We will be follwoing the Data Science Pipeline

  1. Data collection + parsing (if necessary)
  2. Data management
  3. Exploratory data analysis
  4. Hypothesis testing
  5. Communication of insights attained

3. Dataset¶

The objective of this tutorial is to explore and understand the Cost of Living between different countires and how they relate to each other, as well as to determine what factors play the largest role/ a method of predicting the GCL/Salary.

To this end we have obtained the following dataset from kaggle

The dataset is a csv file that contains information about the cost of living in almost 5000 cities across the world. The data was gatthered from Numbeo which describes itself as "The world’s largest cost of living".

Next we will define a new df that will contain four new parameters. These parameters will be indexes that denote the parameter based on some base line to compare the cities with to each other.

Cost of Living Index - a relative parameter that that denotes the Cost of Living based on some base line

Rent Index - a relative parameter that that denotes the Rent based on some base line

Mortgage Rate Index - a relative parameter that that denotes the Mortgage Rate based on some base line

Salary Index - a relative parameter that that denotes the Salary based on some base line

4. Exploration and Data Analysis¶

Distribution Analysis¶

The first thing we want to do is visualize the distributions of our data.

We can create a box plot for each index and view their Central Tendency (mean, mode and median), Dispersion (range, variance), Quartiles (interquartile range), and Standard deviation.

5. Hypothesis Testing¶

Hypothesis: There exist a correlation between the salary of a city and the Cost of Living, Rent, and Mortgage.

Testing H0:β1=0, Ha:β1≠0

To test our hypotheses we will first conduct the Model Utility Test to test if there exist a correlation between our parameters. To do this we will be using statsmodel's OLS Regression.

In [21]:

Random Forest Regression¶

Next we will be using Random Forrests.

Random Forest is an algorithm that uses a modified tree learning algorithm that inspects, at each split in the learning process, a random subset of the features. We will be using Random Search with 10-Fold Cross Validation.

In [27]:
# Random forest Regression
# Split the data into training/testing data using a 80:20 split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(index_df['salary_index'].to_numpy().reshape(-1, 1), index_df['mortgage_index'])

# Tunning of hyper paramemters
# In order to determine the hyperparameters we will be using RandomizedSearchCV with 10-fold cross-validation
# Number of trees in random forest
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 200, stop = 2000, num = 10)]
# Number of features to consider at every split
max_features = ['auto', 'sqrt']
# Maximum number of levels in tree
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, num = 11)]
max_depth.append(None)
# Minimum number of samples required to split a node
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
# Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]
# Method of selecting samples for training each tree
bootstrap = [True, False]

# Create the random grid
random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_features': max_features,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf,
               'bootstrap': bootstrap}
print(random_grid)
rf = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator = RandomForestRegressor(), param_distributions = random_grid, cv = 10, verbose=2, n_jobs = 4)
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(rf.best_params_)

# Create set of predicted values based on the test data
pred = rf.predict(X_test)

# Check Error
errors = abs(pred - y_test)
print('Average Error: {:0.4f} degrees.'.format(np.mean(errors)))

6. Insights and Final Comments¶

From our analysis we have found that there is is a statistically significant correlation betweeen our paramets and that there iss a linear relationship with Salary and Cost of Living.

What this means is that we can confirm that the global cost of living proportionally increases with salary at the rate of 0.3038 and for Rent at the rate of 0.8420 USD. However mortgage decreses at the rate of -1.0696 USD.

From this we can say that while tension may be high at the mommet, our data does not support the idea of a Global Cost of Living Crisis for the time being.
